article.description: The Sacramento Kings gave the Atlanta Hawks a lesson in passing.
article.headline: Kings dominate, 8-23, in turnover ratio
article.linkText: Kings capitalize on Hawks' mistakes for win
article.story: SACRAMENTO (AP) -- When the Sacramento Kings concentrate, they're usually on the way to a blowout win. When they don't, the games get a little tighter and their coach's patience wears a little bit thinner. The concentration came and went Tuesday night as Peja Stojakovic scored 28 points and Brad Miller had 20 points and 10 rebounds in the Kings' fourth straight win, 105-89 over the Atlanta Hawks. Mike Bibby had 19 points and six assists in an impressive statistical game for the Kings, but they still struggled to put away the Hawks in the second half. Sacramento's starters were forced back into the game in the final minutes after Atlanta cut a 24-point deficit to 11. Lapses in focus prevented the Kings from having a cakewalk night before a road game at Seattle on Wednesday, but coach Rick Adelman hopes his team will learn from the experience. "We kept building a lead, and we really couldn't keep our concentration to put them away," Adelman said. "We're just really playing well offensively right now. The ball was really hopping. We're so hard to guard when we're like that ... but then sometimes we forget what works, and we get in trouble." Doug Christie had 13 points, six rebounds and six assists for the Kings, who improved the NBA's best record to 24-8 with their 26th consecutive home win over Eastern Conference teams. Sacramento had 33 assists and just nine turnovers while improving to an NBA-best 18-2 at home, but the Kings weren't satisfied. "We did relax a little bit, and that's not what we need to do," said Stojakovic, the NBA's second-leading scorer. "I guess maybe we're trying to be more exciting than we are. We pass the ball sometimes, and nobody will shoot the ball. But when we play with a lot of intensity and a lot of concentration, we're a tough team to beat." Sacramento increased its Pacific Division lead over the Lakers to a season-high 2½ games after Los Angeles' loss at Minnesota. The Kings, back-to-back division champions, have won eight of their last 10. Shareef Abdur-Rahim and Stephen Jackson each scored 19 points for the last-place Hawks, who dropped to 2-2 on their six-game road trip with their fourth straight loss in Sacramento. Atlanta followed up impressive road wins over Minnesota and Denver with a dismal start against the Kings, falling behind by 23 in the first half. "They came out blazing, hitting everything," Abdur-Rahim said. "Against a team as good as the Kings, you have to come out focused and ready, especially on defense. I'm not sure we came believing we could come in here and win." Sacramento swept its two-game season series with Atlanta for just the second time since 1984-85. The Hawks didn't seem crisp despite shooting 58.8 percent in the first half. Atlanta made 11 turnovers and took silly shots, while the Kings shot better than 71 percent in the first quarter and racked up 20 assists and just three turnovers in the half. "Some guys gave up early," Jackson said. "It's hard to climb back up, and we couldn't get over the hill." The Kings, who never trailed, made a 20-7 run in the third quarter, taking an 81-57 lead midway through. Vlade Divac made up for missing six straight shots with a season-high 10 assists, and Miller added five assists in yet another strong game. Atlanta scored 12 straight points in the fourth quarter to cut Sacramento's lead to 92-81, but Divac and Bibby made free throws before Christie hit Miller for a driving dunk with 2:55 left. "If somebody has a problem with the way we're winning, I don't know what to tell them," said Tony Massenburg, who had 10 points. "All I know is we're winning." Jason Terry was held out of the Hawks' starting lineup with the flu. Jacque Vaughn had 10 points and five assists as the starter, but Atlanta dropped to 0-13 this season when allowing at least 100 points. Game Notes: F Gerald Wallace returned to the Kings after a two-game absence due to the death of a family member. ... The Kings weren't thrilled by the prospect of flying to Seattle after the game. The Pacific Northwest was hit by a snowstorm that forced the postponement of a game in Portland on Tuesday night. ... Bibby and Terry were teammates on Arizona's national championship team in 1997. ... The Kings sold out their 199th consecutive home game.
